        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Base on our requirement, an observation like ALMA with  high angular resolution at arcsec level and  high sensitivity at micron Jy level  is necessary for the Fermi source 2FGL~J1311.7-3429
 to measure the flux at millimeter waveband. We estimate the flux continuum of the synchrotron side  from UV/soft X-ray to Radio 1.4~GHz bands by  a power-law S_{nu} ~ {nu}^{-alpha} with a power index of alpha. Since the flux measured by the LOT static phase  is far away from that measured by the Swift/UVOT AO4 or AO6, we assume the flux detected by Swift/UVOT and  LOT are both in the flare phase. Another assumption is to consider  the detection limit of the WISE, SMA filler,  NVSS, and GBT are the upper limit of the flare phase. Therefore,  the power index alpha is expected to be &lt;0.3. This suggests that the upper limit of the density flux S_{nu} at 100 GHz to be ~0.6 mJy. Besides, base on our Suzaku Observations, the flux variability could be changed for a factor of 10  between the flare phase and the static phase. Therefore,  the upper limit of the flux at ~100 GHz in the static phase is 0.6 mJy/10 = 60 micron Jy.
Therefore, in order to obtain 5 sigma-to-noise level,  we require rms level as 12 micron Jy. We request ALMA band 3 single continuum as our observing band in order to obtain a better sensitivity.
We require synthesized beam of ~1 arcsec for our observation.
The total observation time we need is 2.5 hours.


</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
