    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to search for the millimeter counterpart of the Fermi Object 2FGL J1311.7-3429, which is classified as a radio-quiet gamma-ray millisecond pulsar (MSP). There are only two radio-quiet gamma-ray MSP be found. Although 2FGL J1311.7-3429 is the second one, it has a gamma-ray flux twice higher than the first-found radio-quiet gamma-ray MSP. It is classified as radio-quiet because there is no radio counterpart to be detected. It is believed that the radio emission of pulsars are related to the activity of a polar cap acelerator. However, the minimun flux threshold at radio band is still unknown. We suggest that the radio/mm emission of radio-quiet gamma-ray MSP is at micron Jy level. The mJy sensitivity of the current radio/mm observation is too poor to detect radio/mm emission. ALMA could reach micron Jy level with a few hours, and therefore, is powerful to detect the radio/mm emission of the radio-quiet gamma-ray MSP. This result will be important for us to define or re-define this new-type radio-quiet gamma-ray MSP. On the other hand, if there is still no detection with ALMA sensitivity, we could push the detection limit of  radio-quiet gamma-ray MSP to micron Jy level.

</prp:abstract>
